Add Bearer-token + workspace + subprocess-delegated refresh support
to `opencode attach`.

opencode v1.15.4 supports only HTTP Basic auth on the attach path
(packages/opencode/src/server/auth.ts `header()` returns `Basic <b64>`).
For a remote opencode behind a reverse proxy that does Bearer/JWT
validation (e.g. an OIDC issuer's JWKS), the launcher
needs to:
  - send `Authorization: Bearer <token>` (this patch's --bearer; also
    OPENCODE_SERVER_BEARER env var, which is how kfactory passes the
    initial token without leaking it into /proc/<pid>/cmdline)
  - dispatch a specific workspace (this patch's --workspace -> SDK's
    experimental_workspaceID + ProjectProvider's store.workspace.current
    so the TUI's home prompt uses the right workspace when creating
    new sessions)
  - refresh the access token when it expires, so a TUI session lasting
    > access_token lifetime doesn't drop on SSE reconnect (this patch's
    refresh fetch wrapper)

Refresh strategy: delegate to the launcher via subprocess. The TUI's
fetch wrapper reads `~/.config/kfactory/auth.json` (path passed via
OPENCODE_SERVER_BEARER_CACHE_PATH) on every request, and when the access
token is near expiry spawns `kfactory auth refresh`. kfactory owns the
lockfile, Zitadel HTTP, and atomic-rename of auth.json -- the TUI just
reads the resulting file. This keeps refresh logic in one place (Go,
under kfactory's tests) and removes ~80 LOC of TS that would otherwise
duplicate Go's lockfile + HTTP code.

kfactory must be on the operator's PATH. The TUI runs on the operator's
desktop after `kfactory attach` execs into it; the subprocess refresh is
same-machine, same-UID, same-auth.json.

Server-side opencode doesn't validate Bearer -- the reverse proxy
strips the Authorization header before forwarding. opencode just needs
to send what we tell it.

Upstreamable: bearer + workspace flags + workspace-routing header
